In the StVm plot, F0/F has an increasing trend, the plot is linear and slope of the plot gives KStVm value. KStVm = Kq Γ0 where, Kq is the quenching const. (bimolecular). Γ0 is the PL lifetime of bare BN c-dots. We also measure KStVm and Kq. The value of KStVm obtained is 8.47 × 103 (Kq = 1.1 × 1013). It is observed that the value of KStVm and Kq lies higher than the controlled limit of diffusion indicating the quenching as static quenching. Then TCSPC measurement (shown in Fig. 9a) is performed and it is seen that there is no alteration in FL lifetime of BN c-dots with enhancing the concentration of AM (keeping the BN c-dots' concentration unchanged during the entire experiment). These results guarantee us that there operates static quenching. It can be concluded that BN c-dots' highly conjugated Sp2 core grasp AM via π-π stacking interaction and there is hydrogen bonding interaction between them. So, efficient fluorescence quenching is susceptible to the formation of complex between BN c-dots and AM. We also check the size and the surface charge on BN c-dots by DLS and zeta potential study in the presence of AM solution. The increase in size (Fig. 10
                        ) and alteration in zeta potential (Fig. 11
                        ) of BN c-dots from −20.2 mV to +3.41 mV is observed in the presence of AM confirming about the attachment of AM onto the BN c-dots. To get better idea about the mechanism of quenching, UV–vis spectrum of AM, BN c-dots and BN c-dots with AM were examined and displayed in Fig. 9b. The spectrum of BN c-dots with AM tells that the extra peak formed is due to formation of a new compound via complexation between quencher and BN c-dots indicating static quenching mechanism. TCSPC measurement and size and zeta potential analysis in DLS support the above result confirming the mechanism as static quenching.
